# NativeWind/Gluestack SDUI JSON Rules

## 1. Icons — Use `NavIcon`, Never `Icon` with string `as`

**Problem:** `"type": "Icon"` with `"props": { "as": "SearchIcon" }` passes a string to React, which treats it as an unknown HTML element. Causes "incorrect casing" warnings and renders nothing.

**Fix:** Use `"type": "NavIcon"` with `"props": { "icon": "Search" }`.

```json
// ❌ BAD
{ "type": "Icon", "props": { "as": "SearchIcon", "className": "h-5 w-5" } }

// ✅ GOOD
{ "type": "NavIcon", "props": { "icon": "Search", "size": "sm" } }
```

---

## 2. Select — Use Gluestack Select, Never Custom Components

**Problem:** Custom select components (e.g. `CountrySelect`) duplicate functionality and are not generic.

**Fix:** Use the generic Gluestack `Select` with `SelectTrigger`, `SelectInput`, `SelectIcon`, `SelectPortal`, `SelectBackdrop`, `SelectContent`, and `SelectItem`. Map options via `map` on a wrapper Box with `className: "contents"`. Use `valueChange` action (maps to `onValueChange`):

```json
{
  "type": "Select",
  "props": { "selectedValue": "{{form.countryCode}}" },
  "actions": {
    "valueChange": {
      "type": "runMultiple",
      "actions": [
        { "action": "setState", "payload": { "path": "screens.checkout.form.countryCode", "value": "$event" } }
      ]
    }
  },
  "children": [
    { "type": "SelectTrigger", "children": [
      { "type": "SelectInput", "props": { "placeholder": "Select..." } },
      { "type": "SelectIcon", "children": [{ "type": "NavIcon", "props": { "icon": "ChevronDown", "size": 16 } }] }
    ]},
    { "type": "SelectPortal", "children": [
      { "type": "SelectBackdrop" },
      { "type": "SelectContent", "children": [
        { "type": "Box", "map": "checkout.countries", "key": "opt", "props": { "className": "contents" }, "children": [
          { "type": "SelectItem", "props": { "label": "{{$item.name}}", "value": "{{$item.code}}" } }
        ]}
      ]}
    ]}
  ]
}
```

**Rule:** Never create custom select/dropdown components. Use generic Gluestack Select with `map` for options.

---

## 3. Colors — Use Plain Tailwind, Never CSS Variables

**Problem:** NativeWind's StyleSheet compiler does NOT reliably resolve Tailwind color tokens that reference CSS variables (e.g. `bg-background`, `bg-muted`, `text-foreground`, `border-border`). These silently produce wrong/no colors.

**Fix:** Use plain Tailwind utility classes or hardcoded hex values. Always derive the correct value from the app's `config/theme.json` and `globals.css` and use the actual color directly:

| ❌ CSS Variable Class | ✅ Use Instead |
|---|---|
| `bg-background` | `bg-white` / `bg-gray-950` |
| `bg-muted` | `bg-gray-100` |
| `text-foreground` | `text-gray-900` |
| `text-muted-foreground` | `text-gray-500` |
| `border-border` | `border-gray-200` |
| `bg-primary` | actual hex, e.g. `bg-[#1e293b]` |
| `text-primary-foreground` | `text-white` |
| `bg-destructive` | `bg-red-500` |

The exact replacements depend on the app's design — always check `theme.json` and `globals.css` for the actual values.

---

## 4. Layout — Always `w-full` + `flex-row` for Proper Width & Direction

**Problem 1:** Gluestack `Box` maps to a React Native `View` which does **not** expand to fill its parent width automatically. Without `w-full`, a Box shrinks to its content width — making everything appear centered or squished.

**Problem 2:** `Box` defaults to `flex-col`. Horizontal layouts break silently without `flex-row`.

**Fix:** Add `w-full` to every container that should fill available width, AND add `flex-row` for horizontal layouts:

```json
// ❌ BAD — content appears centered/collapsed
{ "type": "Box", "props": { "className": "max-w-screen-xl mx-auto px-4" } }

// ✅ GOOD — full width then centered max-width
{ "type": "Box", "props": { "className": "w-full max-w-screen-xl mx-auto px-4" } }

// ❌ BAD — will stack vertically even with justify-between
{ "type": "Box", "props": { "className": "flex items-center justify-between" } }

// ✅ GOOD
{ "type": "Box", "props": { "className": "w-full flex flex-row items-center justify-between" } }
```

**Rule:** Every layout wrapper that uses `mx-auto`, `justify-between`, or `grid` must also have `w-full`.

---

## 5. Fixed Navbar — Offset Content Below It

When a layout has a fixed/sticky navbar, the main content area must be padded by the navbar's height to prevent content from being hidden underneath it.

```json
// If navbar is h-16 (64px), the content wrapper needs:
{ "type": "Box", "props": { "className": "flex-1 pt-16" }, "children": [...] }
```

Always match `pt-*` to the actual navbar height defined in the layout.

---

## 6. Theme Switching — Use NativeWind `useColorScheme`

**Problem:** Libraries like `next-themes` conflict with NativeWind's color scheme system.

**Fix:** Use `useColorScheme` from `nativewind` directly in React components registered in the component registry:

```tsx
import { useColorScheme } from "nativewind";
const { colorScheme, setColorScheme } = useColorScheme();
setColorScheme("dark"); // or "light" or "system"
```

**GluestackUIProvider** on web manages the `dark` class on `document.documentElement`. Setting `mode="system"` lets NativeWind control dark mode automatically.

**Design the ThemeSwitcher according to the app's requirements** — it could be a simple toggle, a dropdown, or any other control. Always read the source design spec before implementing. Register it in the component registry so it can be used as `{ "type": "ThemeSwitcher" }` in JSON.

**Closing a dropdown on outside click:**
```tsx
useEffect(() => {
  const handler = (e: MouseEvent) => {
    if (ref.current && !ref.current.contains(e.target as Node)) setOpen(false);
  };
  document.addEventListener("mousedown", handler);
  return () => document.removeEventListener("mousedown", handler);
}, []);
```

